text_answer.content:
Paragraph 2 doesn't explain what 'traditional biomass' is or why we are excluding it for the purposes of discussing hydropower.
Key details question 1 is worded poorly. The percentage of global "primary energy consumption" according to the passage, but that's not the same thing as "total consumption." The other possible answer, A, doesn't answer the question asked.
Answer A is the only non-percentage answer choice for key details question 2
The analyzing information question is very leading and doesn't require students to read/understand the passage to get (for wrong answers that suggest an increase in pollution with the correct answer as the only one which doesn't).

For the inference, "This demonstrates the feasibility of large-scale renewable energy implementation when supported by appropriate policies and infrastructure," "The future of renewable energy looks promising, driven by... supportive policies worldwide." and "The implementation of policies such as the Inflation Reduction Act in the United States, which provides tax credits for new renewable energy projects, further accelerates this transition."
This might be a stretch, but "Countries like Albania, Bhutan, and Iceland are less impacted by environmental pollution." It's supported by the passage, but 'pollution' is a fairly broad term that a) might not account for everything and b) relies heavily on the status of neighboring countries for the statement to be true.
Honestly, I'm struggling to find a reasonable inference here.

text_answer.content:
The vocabulary sentences don't really have anything to do with the topic. Usually they're more closely related. 5 is the only one that has to do with education.
The dress code percents seem questionable. According to Google's AI (so grain of salt), 59% of private schools have a school uniform (something the passage specifically mentions in paragraph 4). Dress codes are far less formal and consistent than school uniforms, so at minimum I'd say we need to combine the data. Taking the information given here and what I found online at face value, it'd be more like 80% of public schools have either a school uniform or dress code while 96% of private schools do. While I can't confirm these numbers are correct, it feels more reasonable for private schools to have that higher percent. Year should also be considered with these statistics when possible. The 2013-2014 school year seemed to have the highest percentage of schools that had a strict dress code, but it's been declining to decades lows since (I could only find to 2020).

I think one of the issues I'm running into in this passage is that there are a LOT of statistics, but no examples of what those statistics specifically mean. It's fine to say "31% of students believe dress codes are unfairly enforced based on gender," and I do respect that the statistic and the reasons behind the statistic are probably true. However, without an example of what the 31% are referring to, it's just a number. Keep in mind that if 31% think this way, 69% don't. It's a percent which could just as easily refer to students who genuinely don't think gender discrimination is happening or it could refer to students who haven't thought about it, so stating what the 31% is talking about is crucial for clarity.
Other questions include: what clothing styles have been unfairly targeted, how have students felt body shamed by dress codes (and how are they even linked), and why are students of color most affected? Again, I do respect that these statements are probably true, but a student who has never had to deal with dress code violations may not have thought about their impact before and won't understand the issues presented.

The hyper focus on statistics means all three Key Details questions are focused on percents.
Key Details question 3 is worded wrong. It's presenting a compare/contrast that requires two statistics (percent of high-poverty vs low-poverty), but it only gives the high-poverty percentage in the answer.
The Analyzing Information question overlaps with Key Details question 2 and the main idea.

For the inference, "schools face the challenge of balancing safety and structure with personal autonomy."
I'm not going give an alternative because I think this passage needs a significant overhaul.

text_answer.content:
Teixobactin is just jargon. I've never seen the word before and I can't even pull the meaning from the context of the sentence - the closest I get is is that it's probably an antibiotic of some sort (the only antibiotic I'd assume high schoolers know is penicillin).  A quick Google search confirms it is and antibiotic, but it was only discovered in 2015
The analyzing information and key details 1 questions focus on the same fact - some antibiotics attack bacterial cell walls. The focus is a little different, so it may not be a problem.
For the inference, I'd argue both A and E are valid. A is obviously the correct answer, but E is also reasonable since the discovery of penicillin meant the discovery of antibiotics in general - meaning it was more important than any subsequent antibiotic development. It's one of those pedantic answers that some students will push for even if they know which one is 'supposed' to be the right answer.

Prompt 1 is bad. Because of the subtle, probably benign, bias in the passage, there are no apparent risks to drone usage. Students unfamiliar with the technology won't be able to answer that aspect of the question.
For prompt 2, AI is outside the scope of the passage as written.
"Do you think there's a downside to using drones for agricultural purposes? Explain your answer." - Similar to prompt 1, but it acknowledges upfront that students are going to have to think of their own answer (including the possibility of 'no') without the direct help of the passage.
"What drone features mentioned in the passage would be most useful outside of agriculture and why?"

text_answer.content:
Vocabulary sentences 2 and 4 are basically definitions of their respective words. The sentences also have very little to do with the passage.
Another soft yes on bias. There are negatives to EVs, specifically the process of mining the necessary resources to make the batteries (there are environmental and geopolitical issues). I'm not sure including this information is required, but flagging so a decision can be made.
I'm not sure the sequence in the Analyzing Information question is fully supported. Although level 1, dedicated home charging stations, and level 3 fast-charging stations are mentioned in that order, the trend is more related to fastest/most effective charging methods, not the order each was developed. This might be due to the question being a little unclear, but I always associate the word evolution with an element of 'over time.'

For the inference question, answer E is basically the last two sentences of the passage. The words are different, but the meaning is the same.
B is a reasonable answer. It does require some minimal outside knowledge, but I'd personally say it's in the 'common knowledge' category. The only two meaningful commercial engines types besides electric are gas and diesel, and diesel is limited to larger vehicles like trucks and semis. Therefore B is reasonable.
If you don't want to include an answer that requires any outside knowledge, however, you can change the word gasoline to combustion and it'd be within the scope of the passage.

text_answer.content:
Flavonoids and phthalates are jargon.
I understand what the passage means when it says microwave radiation cooks food more evenly, but because of how microwaves, the appliances, are built that statement becomes not entirely true (the scenario where parts of the meal are boiling hot while other parts are still ice cold).

This passage is far too surface level for the topic for 11th graders.
Paragraphs 2 and 3 say basically the same thing.
Definitely want paragraph 4 to explain its information better. The only thing we've been told is that microwaves excite water molecules, so how are plastic containers affected exactly and why does that translate to dangers?

The Analyzing Information question answers itself.

For the inference question, I don't agree with the answer. "Contrary to popular misconceptions" doesn't necessarily translate to "significant misconceptions." Flat earth is a popular misconception, but it's not a significant one since a good chunk of the attention on this topic comes from people mocking the bad science.
I do feel this passage requires a substantial edit, so I'm not going to give an alternative right now.

text_answer.content:
Yottawatt and tokamak are jargon.
A pedantic yes on false information. Without the sun, our planet wouldn't exist. Gravitational forces play a large part in Earth's creation, including and especially those from the sun. However, that's outside the scope of the passage, so while the statement is technically wrong, the picture it paints is maybe more important than the technical accuracy in this case.
All thee Key Details questions are stats focused. At least one should be something else.
Although correct, I'm not a huge fan of the inference here. There's minimal discussion of the technology involved in nuclear fusion, only that there the extreme conditions make the process challenging. I actually like the inference that "The sun is constantly losing mass," which is supported by the discussions of E=mc^2 but never directly stated.

text_answer.content:
I've commented on this topic before being a little unrealistic. Looking it up, I realize now that it's partially because the definition of 'smart city' is fairly wide. According to some, there are no smart cities within the USA, but others list NYC, Boston, and Chicago (despite these cities not fully integrating some of these technologies). A slight refocus might be required here to help students better understand how the technology here is being practically implemented in actual cities. Singapore is probably the best choice as a main focus. Basically take the last paragraph and make that the essay instead of what's written here.
The passage also feels a little like it's trying to sell me on smart cities. What are some of the issues that have arisen or aren't fully addressed within cities like Singapore.  Even the Key Idea is a thesis statement. The Inference answer also supports this idea of a bias by directly point out that traditional cities (which is still somewhat undefined) will struggle because they're not smart cities.
Both Key Details 3 and Analyzing Information are related to the Smart Nation program.
